pr_review_comment_body:
This isn't quite right. It should be:

```javascript
    modelEvents() {
        // Simple properties:
        const properties = [
            ['title', 'hover_text']
        ]
        properties.forEach(([nameInView, nameInModel]) => {
            const callback = (
                () => {
                  this.marker.set(
                  nameInView, this.model.get(nameInModel))
                }
            )
            this.model.on(`change:${nameInModel}`, callback, this)
        })

        const infoBoxProperties = [
            ['content', 'info_html']
            // 'content' is the name of the property for the InfoWindow object,
            // 'info_html' is the name of the property in the Python widget
        ]
        infoBoxProperties.forEach(([nameInView, nameInModel]) => {
            const callback = (
                () => {
                    this.infoWindow.set(
                    nameInView, this.model.get(nameInModel))
                }
            )
            this.model.on(`change:${nameInModel}`, callback, this)
        })

        this.setStyleEvents()
    }
```

The idea is that, every time the property `info_html` is changed at the Python level, this triggers an event in JS called `change:info_html` (by the magic of traitlets and ipywidgets). We need to react to that event by changing the property in the google maps `InfoWindow` object.

This lets us change the info text without having to redraw the entire map:

<img width="1112" alt="screen shot 2016-12-11 at 14 19 02" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1392879/21080669/1b310b44-bfad-11e6-80ef-b6b8ba9e955b.png">

Ultimately, listening to events and handling them correctly should let people build mini-applications running in Jupyter notebooks.

I'd be happy to kill `add_header` (in fact I'd started to do that before I reined in the changes) but in that case it's not just the `headers` setter that needs changing, rather `headers` itself needs to have different behavior.

It would be like this (untested, just for discussion):
```python
class HeadersDict(CaseInsensitiveDict):
    def __setitem__(key, value):
        if isinstance(value, (tuple, list)):
            value = value[0]
        super(HeadersDict, self).__setitem__(key, value)
```

and then I'd move the giant docstring from `VCR` down to `HeadersDict`

