I am still not convinced with way we are getting cloud object. `Cloud.get_cloud()` will always return new object of a cloud. I think we can move `get_cloud()` in `qubole.py`. It can look like: 

``` python
    def get_cloud(cls, cloud_provider_name=None):
       if cloud_provider_name:
         // create a new cloud object here because cloud provider name is explicitly passed 
       else:
        // return cls.cloud it is already set. 
         if cls.cloud is not None: 
             return cls.cloud;
          // create it, set it at class level and return that
         if (cls.cloud_provider == "aws")
            cls.cloud = new AwsCloud()
         elif(cls.cloud_provider == "azure") 
            cls.cloud = new AzureCloud()
         return cls.cloud; 
```

Set cloud_provider_name from the options passed by the user. 
This approach is similar to how we cache connection agent

I understand your concern because of the change of behavior with regards to the old tool-chain.
The solution to this is a binder: https://developer.android.com/guide/components/bound-services.html

Example from http://stackoverflow.com/a/24541584
```
import android.app.Service;
import android.content.Intent;
import android.os.IBinder;

public class MyService extends Service {
    private Binder binder;  

    @Override
    public void onCreate() {
        super.onCreate();
        binder = new Binder();
    }

    @Override
    public IBinder onBind(Intent intent) {
        return binder;
    }

    public class Binder extends android.os.Binder {
        public MyService getService() {
            return MyService.this;
        }
    }
}
```

